Based on the provided HTML structure and assuming a basic styling from `Style.css` (which isn't shared), here are some theme change suggestions to enhance the visual appeal of your blog posts:

**Color Scheme:**

* **Light Theme (Default):**
	+ Background: `#F7F7F7` (a soft, neutral gray)
	+ Text: `#333333` (a deep, rich gray for readability)
	+ Links: `#007bff` (a calming blue) with a hover effect to `#0056b3`
	+ Headers (h1, h2): `#212121` (a darker gray for contrast)
* **Dark Theme:**
	+ Background: `#333333` (a deep, rich gray)
	+ Text: `#FFFFFF` (white) or `#F7F7F7` (soft gray for reduced glare)
	+ Links: `#66d9ef` (a soft, pastel blue) with a hover effect to `#3e8e41`
	+ Headers (h1, h2): `#FFFFFF` (white) or `#F7F7F7` (soft gray for contrast)

**Typography:**

* Font Family: Open Sans or Merriweather (for a more readable, modern look)
* Font Sizes:
	+ h1: 24px - 30px
	+ h2: 18px - 22px
	+ Body Text: 16px

**Additional Styling:**

* **Padding and Margins:** Ensure sufficient spacing between elements for a clean layout. For example, `body { padding: 20px; }` and adjust margins for headers and paragraphs as needed.
* **Link Underlines:** Consider removing underlines for links in the light theme or styling them to match the link color in the dark theme for a cleaner appearance.
* **Header Styles:** Add a subtle shadow or border to differentiate headers (h1, h2) from the rest of the content.
* **List Styling (for your post lists):**
	+ Remove default list bullets and use a custom icon or a simple `` character for a minimalist look.
	+ Style list items with a bottom border or a slight padding to separate each item.

**Example CSS Snippets (assuming you're starting from a basic PureCSS setup):**

```css
/* Style.css (example snippets) */

body {
  font-family: 'Open Sans', sans-serif;
  line-height: 1.6;
}

.light-theme {
  background-color: #F7F7F7;
  color: #333333;
}

.light-theme a {
  color: #007bff;
  text-decoration: none;
}

.light-theme a:hover {
  color: #0056b3;
}

.dark-theme {
  background-color: #333333;
  color: #FFFFFF;
}

.dark-theme a {
  color: #66d9ef;
  text-decoration: none;
}

.dark-theme a:hover {
  color: #3e8e41;
}

h1, h2 {
  font-weight: bold;
  margin-bottom: 0.5em;
}

h1 {
  font-size: 26px;
}

h2 {
  font-size: 20px;
  color: #212121; /* Adjust for dark theme as needed */
}

ul {
  list-style: none;
  padding: 0;
  margin: 0;
}

li {
  padding: 10px;
  border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; /* Adjust color based on theme */
}

li:last-child {
  border-bottom: none;
}
```

**Apply Button for Theme Switching (updated):**

To match the suggested themes, update your `applyTheme` function in `script.js` to toggle between `.light-theme` and `.dark-theme` classes on the `<body>` element instead of directly applying theme classes.

```javascript
// script.js (updated applyTheme function)

function applyTheme(theme) {
  document.body.classList.remove('light-theme', 'dark-theme');
  document.body.classList.add(theme);
}
```

Remember, these are just starting points. Feel free to experiment and adjust the styles according to your personal preferences or brand identity. If you have `Style.css` specifics you'd like me to work with, please share them for more tailored suggestions.

